text.text:
Visited December 16, 2025

Five stars without hesitation. We are heading out tomorrow on a 17 day cruise to Hawaii and flew into San Francisco a day early to settle in and enjoy the city. My original plan for lunch was Chinese food, but I opened my big mouth and told my kids a story from 2020. When we were in LA on our way to Hawaii back then, we stopped at In N Out. My husband and I thought our older daughter, who was not even two at the time, would share the burger with us. Instead she ate the entire thing herself and my husband had to go get another one. üòÜ

That story completely sealed our fate. My older daughter refused anything but In N Out, so from the Marriott Marquis where we are staying, we hopped on the cable car and rode all the way there. The place was absolutely packed, but the energy was great and the line moved efficiently. Despite how busy it was, the staff remained friendly, calm, and welcoming, and we were lucky enough to manage getting a table.

A special shout out to Dino who was bussing tables. He was incredibly attentive and kind. He noticed our two little girls right away and surprised them with kids activity books, which completely made their day. He checked on us several times, brought extra napkins, and made sure we were comfortable the entire time. That level of genuine care really stood out.

For the girls, we ordered two Double Doubles with just cheese, cheese fries, and chocolate milkshakes. For my husband and me, we ordered two Double Doubles with added chilies and grilled onions along with Animal Fries. We made our lemon up ourselves and it was so fresh and so good. Every single bite was delicious and absolutely worth the trip. The food was hot, fresh, and exactly as remembered, maybe even better.

After eating, we took the cable car straight back to the hotel and everyone promptly passed out. Waking up at 1 am was no fun, but this experience was completely worth it and gave us such a fun family memory right before our cruise.

The only small hiccup was entirely on us. We forgot hand sanitizer and the restaurant did not have any available. My six year old had basically touched everything on the cable car üòÜ so my husband walked across the street to buy some and paid six dollars for a tiny bottle that would normally cost a dollar elsewhere. Oh well üòÜüòÜ

Overall, the food, the service, and the kindness of the staff made this an easy five star experience. Thank you to Dino and the entire team for such a memorable and welcoming visit. We loved every single moment and every bite.

text.text:
It seems that in the great state of California, one cannot speak of cuisine without mentioning a fabled establishment In-N-Out Burger. My partner insisted it was an experience one must have, a culinary rite of passage, a sacred tradition.

So, on a lazy afternoon, we decided to indulge this local enthusiasm. The place positively brimming with life, a bustling crowd united by their devotion to burgers and the faint scent of grilled promise. Clearly, this was no ordinary eatery; it was a cult favourite.

I wouldn‚Äôt dare compare it to the gourmet creations of fine restaurants, where one must decipher menus and pay for artistic interpretation and to be honest that wouldn‚Äôt be a fair at all. For fast food, it was most commendable. The flavor was honest, the texture agreeable and it does sit in the upper level of fast food burger hierarchy.

It was a charmingly sincere experience and I see the point my partner was trying to make.

editorialSummary.text: Luxe landmark lodging offering plush quarters, some with bay views, plus refined dining & a spa.

text.text:
Travelled from Melbourne , Australia to stay here for 2 nights 12th and 13th December. The hotel itself is visibly stunning! It felt so festive & lovely when we walked in. Unfortunately due to the level of popularity the Christmas display attracts - it‚Äôs makes it very difficult for hotel guests to walk around without disrupting photos being taken & bumping into families with children. Would recommend having select times for access.

Check in process - not great - although the staff member was delightful, we were given poor directions resulting in quite a delay getting into our room when it was late.

The room was lovely looking HOWEVER noticed the bathroom sink had green mildew in it. (The hole at the front). The hairdryer - likely from when the hotel was first constructed - for such a lovely hotel, would strongly recommend upgrading these for female guests - not to mention it being a fire hazard with so much dust built up on the filter.  TV - very small for such a large room and difficult to see when you are in bed.
Beds were very comfortable, lovely linen and toiletries were beautiful.

We were really looking forward to enjoying a drink in the palm court restaurant , however after purchasing -was told we were unable to sit on the tables as they were being set up for ‚Äúa full lunch service‚Äù. This left hotel guests no where to sit. Disappointing for paying guests, unable to use facilities freely due to it ‚Äúbeing a popular time of year ‚Äú.

text.text:
I stayed at the Fairmont San Francisco during a recent trip, and it really does live up to its reputation. The hotel itself feels like a historic landmark, and walking into the lobby is almost like stepping into another era. Everything is polished, elegant, and very well kept. The staff greeted me right away, helped with bags, and made the check in process simple. It was clear they took pride in taking care of people.

My room had a great view over the city, and the space felt comfortable and quiet. The bed was probably one of the best I have slept in during a hotel stay, and the bathroom had plenty of counter space and good lighting. Housekeeping kept everything spotless the entire time, and every request I made was handled quickly. Even something small like asking for extra towels felt like it mattered to them.

The location on Nob Hill is also perfect if you want to explore. You can walk to a lot of places if you do not mind the hills, and it is easy to grab a cable car or rideshare when you want to get across town. I enjoyed the restaurants inside the hotel as well, especially for breakfast. The Fairmont is not the cheapest option in the city, but for a special trip or a visit where you want everything to feel a little elevated, it is definitely worth it. I would stay here again without hesitation.

content.text: This central area of San Francisco, nestled between Chinatown and Nob Hill, offers a mix of bustling urban life and cultural experiences. The proximity to attractions like Union Square, the Cable Car Museum, and SF Masonic Auditorium makes it a great location for exploring the city.

Chinatown, a historically rich and vibrant neighborhood, features authentic Chinese cuisine and cultural highlights like the Dragon Gate and Tin How Temple. Grace Cathedral, known for its architectural beauty and tranquil atmosphere, hosts a variety of activities. Public transportation, including buses and cable cars, provides convenient access to the city.

editorialSummary.text: Bustling Italian eatery with varied pizza options from coal-fired to Roman-style, plus beer on tap.

text.text:
Delicious, authentic, romantic, and delicious!!
Went for dinner around 7:30 pm on a Thursday with my girlfriend and there was no wait for a table outside. The patio Christmas decor was so pretty and the ambiance of the place was so warm and welcoming.
We couldn‚Äôt decide between the New Yorker, the Burratina, and the Porto; all award winning pizzas.
The burratina is a thick crust pizza on the focaccia so we didn‚Äôt get that since it would‚Äôve been a lot of food for us. We ordered the Porto. The crust was so thin and had the perfect balance between fluffy and soft. The ndjua was delicious on it but this pizza is more on the umami side of flavors. We wish we got one of the classic pizzas, but definitely coming back to try it out.
We also got the Pasta Genovesa, which we lovedddd. The pesto was super rich and every ingredient in the dish was perfectly balanced. Fresh sundried tomatoes, artichokes, pine nuts, goat cheese. Honestly would come back just for that.

We also got the Tirramisu for dessert! Absolutely must must get!

We got the Detroit and the coal fire - the Detroit was impressive, fresh tomatoes and the Parmesan crusted edge was crispy but not burnt - very tasty.

My only complaint (and this happens with a lot of pizza spots) is they put a salad on top of the pizza - I find it completely unnecessary. But that can just be customized.

The coal fire was thin and charred well but too many toppings and it just got too floppy. I think the New York style or New Haven style would have been better to order. I did like the pepperonis on it though.

Also, 2 pizzas is enough for 4 people. Kinda wish they had smaller versions of pies so you get to try more.

text.text:
I finally had the chance to taste what is arguably the most famous burrito in all of SF. I went close to noon on weekday, and the queue was about 15 minutes long. The line moves incredibly fast, and before I knew I was already placing my order. I got the burrito they are known for which is their carne asada super burrito. I got it toasted. You place your order at the front, and then you go inside and pay your bill, and then you wait for them to call your number. The inside of the restaurant is packed, and often you will be sharing your table with other Diners, making it a very communal form of dining. My burrito took about 10 minutes to arrive, and it was probably the best burrito I have ever eaten. It wasn‚Äôt as hefty as other burritos, given the lack of rice, which gives it volume, but the meat was so tender, the beans were so well seasoned, and the sour cream, and the guac was so creamy. This was such a satisfying burrito and also the perfect portion size for one person.

I will definitely be back, but I also want to try some other burritos in the neighbourhood.

You place your order at the front, and then you go inside and pay your bill, and then you wait for them to call your number. The inside of the restaurant is packed, and often you will be sharing your table with other Diners, making it a very communal form of dining. My burrito took about 10 minutes to arrive, and it was probably the best burrito I have ever eaten. It wasn‚Äôt as hefty as other burritos, given the lack of rice, which gives it volume, but the meat was so tender, the beans were so well seasoned, and the sour cream, and the guac was so creamy. This was such a satisfying burrito and also the perfect portion size for one person.

I will definitely be back, but I also want to try some other burritos in the neighbourhood.

text.text:
I‚Äôve seen all the Instagram videos, heard all the hype, and read all the claims that La Taqueria serves some of the best Mexican food in the country. I finally made the trip, and honestly, I‚Äôm glad I did. The food really is as good as everyone says‚Äîan easy 10 out of 10.

That being said, this place definitely has its cons. You should expect a very long line almost any day of the week. On a lucky day, the wait might be around 20‚Äì30 minutes, but it can go much longer. Once you finally reach the front and place your order, you‚Äôll notice the staff is working incredibly fast. They‚Äôre not rude at all‚Äîthey‚Äôre just in non-stop hustle mode, so don‚Äôt expect a warm chatty environment.

After ordering, two new challenges start: finding a seat and waiting for your food. The inside is very small, cramped, and not the most comfortable place to sit. The last time I visited, the food took almost an hour after ordering. It sounds crazy, but the moment the food arrives, everything changes.

The burritos here truly are on another level. I recommend ordering Mission Style (no rice), which lets the flavors stand out‚Äîthe guacamole, the steak, the little green beans, everything. They‚Äôre generous with the guac, the meat is amazing, and the flavors are insanely well-balanced. You can also ask for Dorado (toasted). I usually say ‚ÄúMission Style, Dorado,‚Äù and it comes out perfectly crispy all around.

Even with the long lines, the tight seating, and the slow wait inside, the food makes up for every single flaw. It really is the best burrito I‚Äôve ever had. I hope one day they expand or speed up the line, but for now, it‚Äôs still absolutely worth the hype. This place is magical and a must-try.

text.text:
In-N-Out Burger is one of those places that feels simple in the best way possible. The menu is short, which honestly makes ordering less stressful, and everything feels intentional. You go there knowing you‚Äôre getting burgers, fries, and shakes‚Äîno distractions. The burgers are fresh, juicy, and taste like they were actually made when you ordered, not pulled from a heat lamp. The toasted buns and crisp lettuce make everything feel balanced instead of greasy.

The fries are probably the most debated part. On their own, they‚Äôre hit or miss since they‚Äôre fresh-cut and not super crispy, but ordering them ‚Äúanimal style‚Äù changes everything. With cheese, grilled onions, and sauce, they‚Äôre way more satisfying. The shakes are thick, classic, and not overly sweet, which makes them easy to finish.

What really stands out is the price and consistency. For how good the food is, it‚Äôs surprisingly affordable, especially compared to other fast-food chains. The staff is usually friendly and upbeat, and the restaurant stays pretty clean even when it‚Äôs packed. Overall, In-N-Out isn‚Äôt trying to be fancy‚Äîit just does fast food really well, and that‚Äôs why people love it.

We were beyond impressed with the entire operation at In-N-Out from the moment we pulled in to the moment we left. The food exceeded expectations ‚Äî the burgers were juicy and flavorful with perfectly crisp buns, and the French fries tasted incredibly fresh, cooked to that ideal balance of not too soft and not too hard. It‚Äôs rare to see such efficiency and quality in such a busy setting. This In-N-Out sets the bar high for fast food ‚Äî highly recommend stopping by!

text.text:
Visiting Tartine Bakery was honestly one of those ‚Äúthis is why people rave about it‚Äù moments for me. The moment I walked in, the smell of freshly baked bread and butter-heavy pastries was irresistible.

I tried their croissant and the famous Morning Bun, and both were absolutely worth the hype. The croissant was perfectly flaky on the outside and soft inside, while the Morning Bun had this beautiful balance of sweetness, cinnamon, and citrus that made it unforgettable. You can truly taste the craftsmanship in every bite.

Yes, there was a line‚Äîbut it moved quickly, and the energy inside was lively and warm. It felt like a place where food is taken seriously, but without any pretension.

My takeaway:
Tartine Bakery is not just a bakery, it‚Äôs an experience. If you‚Äôre in San Francisco and love good bread and pastries, this place deserves a spot on your list. I‚Äôd happily wait in that line again.

text.text:
Another chilly but gorgeous morning in San Francisco and I am hungry. So I whip out my iPhone and use Google Maps to search for breakfast spots near the Mission District. Fortunately for me, Tartine Bakery pops up and I decide to head over.

I actually find parking pretty quickly, and I know that I got lucky. I lock up my car and walk over and as soon as I cross walk in the door, I smell deliciousness. I check out the display case and I pick a yummy looking scone and order the breakfast sandwich. I take my number and sit by the window. The bakery is busy and happy patrons chat while enjoying their food. The vibe is busy, but relaxed, warm and friendly A few minutes later, my breakfast sandwich is hand delivered and it looks tasty.

The golden toasted crust of the bread mixed with the soft savory scrambled eggs is the perfect answer to my hunger. I try to eat slowly so as to thoroughly enjoy my meal, but the sandwich is gone too quickly.

What can I say. It was scrumptious! I will definitely eat there again the next time that I‚Äôm in the Mission District.

And I haven‚Äôt even mentioned the food which was excellent. Had to go with the King Henry VIII cut and I finished that along with the bonus portion you get for finishing it. The flavor was spot on but the tenderness and texture is what really sets it apart. Also that creamed spinach is as good as everyone says it is.
As a Prime Rib enthusiast, this place has been on my list for a long time and I am so glad to have finally made the pilgrimage and look forward to returning as soon as I can.

text.text: We enjoyed our visit to The Grove. It was very easy to order and find a seat. Matter of fact we had a wheelchair in our party and the man that was at the entrance welcoming us made sure that he found us a personal table to accommodate our party of six including the wheelchair. The food came out very promptly, fresh and hot. The servers were outstanding, they made sure we always had what we needed and brought it to us promptly. The cocktails were scrumptious and creative! We had three burgers which were made to well done. If you like yiur burger less done I would recommend ordering it medium rare. I had the chicken pot pie which was good, wish it had a little bit more seasoning. The two dessert cakes were outstanding.

The atmosphere is killer. Loved how it looks inside with the huge trees, lights, and multiple floors. It‚Äôs almost like one of those romantic movie film sets.

I got the breakfast burrito and my wife got the eggs Benedict. Do be aware that a lot of San Francisco restaurants add on a ‚Äúmandate‚Äù charge for their employees health care that the customer has to pay for instead of the company. Beyond that, the food is reasonably priced for what you get.

Honestly I‚Äôm a bit torn. I loved the food, I loved the atmosphere, but it‚Äôs self-serve in that you can‚Äôt sit still a table until you order; and even then it‚Äôs basically cafeteria style with order and pay and then get a number. No service per say. But the food is great and the atmosphere is killer. So yeah. I‚Äôd definitely purely come back!

text.text:
I have been to The Grove many times.  In a nutshell, the restaurant suffers from inconsistency and problems in execution by the kitchen and the servers.  In my many experiences, mostly breakfast, there are issues with the food that come out from the kitchen. Today, I ordered a simple classic breakfast plate: Eggs (choice of scrambled, poached or fried, i.e sunny side up or over easy), Rosemary Hash Browns and Bacon Strips, with batard toast. I asked for the hash browns "crispy" because, well, mushy hash browns defeat the purpose don't they?

The plate I received had cold toast, coolish hash browns (with a crispy crust, though), and limp, room temperature bacon. The fried eggs were warm but the yolks were hard as rocks. WAY overcooked. The bacon was completely limp - flaccid and room temperature. Not appetizing, and irritating when you are paying $28 with tips and taxes and service fees.

What is particularly sad is the bacon was clearly high quality bacon. The hash browns were well seasoned. The Bayard toast would have been fantastic, if it had been served within the zip code of warm.  The owners clearly care about the quality of the food, it is conceived well, and it is made with quality ingredients. The problem is that the kitchen does not seem able to execute on eggs ( not once in many visits for me, but somehow my wife's poached eggs were poached correctly today, something the restaurant has never been able to achieve for me and why I quit ordering the Eggs Benedict because hard egg yolks suck, and egg whites should be included in a poached egg. The kitchen staff cannot understand how to coordinate the components of the plate to be served together hot (or even warm), and the serving staff clearly pays no attention to checking whether the plate is suited to be served. This has ever been my gripe with The Grove - all promise, always complete failure on the final execution.

So why 3 stars? Always greeted at door with friendly staff passing out me us and welcoming you. Warm and friendly atmosphere. Nice seating areas create a truly nice ambiance. The menu is well thought out, quality ingredients. The juices are top notch. If they could just get staff in the kitchen and serving the food to care and coordinate, and to have consistency.

Personally, I am tapped out on chances for them to pull it all together, sadly. Cafe De La Presse and dozens of others get the eggs and service right on with 100% accuracy. It is sad The Grove - which should be able to do the same - fails so utterly when they clearly have quality in mind - is simply baffling.
